      "title": "Before the Giant",
      "subject": "Series: Compete Differently. A seven-day faith performance plan that helps athletes compete from identity, trust God beyond outcomes, stay focused in storms, remain faithful when progress is slow, steward their gifts, hear God in quiet places, and run for the prize that lasts.",
      "releaseDate": releaseDate,
      "challengeDay": "Day 1",
      "challengeLength": 7,
      "steps": [
"Mental Model\n\nThe Battle Everyone Saw Wasn't the Battle That Made David\nStory\nImagine being handed the biggest opportunity of your life...\nNot because you've earned it in everyone else's eyes...\nBut because everyone else is too afraid to take it.\nThat was David.\nMost people remember him as the young shepherd who killed a giant with a sling and a stone.\nWhat they forget is that David wasn't supposed to be there.\nHe wasn't a soldier.\nHe wasn't wearing armor.\nHe wasn't even old enough to be in the army.\nHe had simply been sent by his father to deliver food to his older brothers on the battlefield.\nWhen David arrived, he found something surprising.\nFor forty straight days, the entire army of Israel had stood frozen.\nEvery morning, the giant Goliath walked into the valley and shouted the same challenge.\n\"Send me one man to fight.\"\nEvery morning...\nSilence.\nThese weren't ordinary men.\nMany were trained warriors.\nThey had better weapons than David.\nMore experience.\nMore strength.\nMore reasons to believe they should be the ones stepping forward.\nYet nobody moved.\nNot because they lacked ability...\nBecause fear had become louder than faith.\nThen David heard the giant.\nBut he heard something else too.\nWhile everyone else focused on the size of Goliath...\nDavid focused on the greatness of God.\nThe same words that filled everyone else with fear filled David with conviction.\nKing Saul couldn't understand it.\nDavid's own brother accused him of showing off.\nEven Saul tried to convince him he wasn't qualified.\n\"You're only a boy.\"\nImagine hearing that moments before the biggest challenge of your life.\nMost people would've turned around.\nDavid didn't.\nInstead, he began telling a story.\nNot about the giant.\nAbout the lion.\nAbout the bear.\nYears earlier, while no one was watching, predators had attacked the sheep David was\nresponsible for protecting.\nHe could've run.\nNobody would've blamed him.\nAfter all, they were just sheep.\nInstead, David chased the lion.\nHe fought the bear.\nNot because anyone was keeping score.\nNot because there would be applause afterward.\nBut because that's what faithfulness required.\nThose lonely fields became David's training ground.\nEvery ordinary day with those sheep was preparing him for an extraordinary day in the valley.\nDavid said something that changes the way we should think about confidence forever.\n\"The Lord who rescued me from the lion and the bear will rescue me from this Philistine.\"\nNotice what David didn't say.\nHe didn't say...\n\"I think I can do it.\"\n\"I've been practicing.\"\n\"I'm talented.\"\nHis confidence wasn't rooted in himself.\nIt was rooted in God's faithfulness.\nBy the time David walked toward Goliath...\nThe battle had already been won inside his heart.\nThe giant was simply the stage where everyone else got to witness what God had been building\nin private.\nPull Back the Curtain\nMost athletes believe confidence comes from winning.\nWin enough games...\nHit enough home runs...\nScore enough points...\nEventually you'll become confident.\nDavid's life tells a completely different story.\nConfidence isn't created by public victories.\nIt's created through private faithfulness.\nThink about it.\nDavid didn't suddenly become courageous when he saw Goliath.\nHe simply responded the way he had trained himself to respond for years.\nEvery time he protected another sheep...\nHe was building trust.\nEvery lonely afternoon in the field...\nHe was learning obedience.\nEvery unseen victory became another reminder that God had never abandoned him before.\nBy the time Goliath appeared, David wasn't trying to manufacture confidence.\nHe was remembering God's track record.\nThat's what faith does.\nFaith isn't pretending you aren't scared.\nFaith is choosing to remember who God has already proven Himself to be.\nAs an athlete, your \"lion and bear\" moments probably don't look like David's.\nThey're the early morning workouts when nobody else is awake.\nThe extra swings after practice.\nThe decision to encourage a teammate instead of complaining.\nThe choice to keep showing up after a terrible game.\nThe moments nobody posts online.\nThose are the fields where God builds competitors.\nLong before He ever gives them a giant.\nPractice Install\nToday, stop looking for your Goliath.\nLook for your sheep.\nFind one small responsibility you've been overlooking and do it with excellence.\nRun every sprint through the line.\nPut your shopping cart back.\nHelp clean up after practice without being asked.\nEncourage the teammate who usually gets ignored.\nDo the unseen work as if God Himself were watching.\nBecause He is.\nThe habits you build in ordinary moments are preparing you for extraordinary ones.\nJournal\nDavid remembered the lion and the bear before he faced Goliath.\nTake a few minutes and write down three times God has already been faithful in your life.\nThey don't have to be dramatic.\nMaybe He gave you strength after an injury.\nMaybe He opened a door you didn't expect.\nMaybe He carried you through a season you thought would break you.\nNow ask yourself:\nHow would remembering God's faithfulness change the way you approach your next game,\npractice, or challenge?\nFinal Thought\nEveryone wants a giant-sized testimony.\nVery few people are willing to embrace shepherd-sized faithfulness.\nThe world celebrates what happens in the valley.\nGod often does His greatest work in the pasture.\nNever underestimate the quiet seasons of your life.\nBecause the place that feels unnoticed today may be the very place God is using to prepare you\nfor the moment everyone else will remember."
      ]
